STRONGOPS()                                                        STRONGOPS()



NNAAMMEE
       ssttrroonnggooppss - Register with StrongOps

       The  "strongops"  command  registers users with the StrongOps platform.
       The simplest usage is ssllcc ssttrroonnggooppss. The command prompts for user name,
       email and a password and then displays the credentials to standard out-
       put, if the credentials were not written to a file. If no command  line
       options  are  given  for  name or email, the strongops command tries to
       find defaults from ~~//..ggiittccoonnffiigg (name  and  email)  and  then  ~~//..nnppmmrrcc
       (email).  However,  when you specify valid options on the command line,
       there are no interactive prompts for the data specified on the  command
       line.

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       slc strongops [options]

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       ----nnaammee Specify  the  full user name, e.g.: ----nnaammee ''BBoobb RRoobbeerrttss'' (quotes
              are needed as the full name contains a space).

       ----eemmaaiill
              Specify the email address, e.g.: ----eemmaaiill ssoommeeoonnee@@ssttrroonngglloooopp..ccoomm.

       ----ppaasssswwoorrdd
              Specify your StrongOps password, e.g.: ----ppaasssswwoorrdd 1122334455667788

       ----nnoossaavvee
              Prevent saving of StrongOps account credentials, this  overrides
              any save option.

       ----llooccaall
              Saves StrongOps account credentials in a ..//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn file.

       ----ppaacckkaaggee
              Saves  StrongOps  account credentials in ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn file, if
              the file exists.

       ----gglloobbaall
              Saves StrongOps account credentials in a ~~//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn file.

       ----ssaavveeaallll
              Saves  StrongOps  account  credentials   to   ..//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn,
              ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn and ~~//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn files.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
       The  following will have strongops prompt for the name, email and pass-
       word. The JSON containing the strongops credentials are sent  to  stan-
       dard output:



               $ slc strongops



       Next,  the  strongops credentials are saved to the local ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn
       file:



               $ slc strongops --package



       By using the options for name, email  and  password,  you  can  have  a
       non-interactive registration, e.g. that will not prompt:



               $ slc strongops --name "Bill Williams" --email "bw@strongops.com" --password "12345678"



       Using  the  saveall  option causes strongops to save the credentials to
       ..//ppaacckkaaggee..jjssoonn, ..//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn and ~~//ssttrroonngglloooopp..jjssoonn:



               $ slc strongops --saveall






